The tenant of Bakal: The stove is heating up, he signed a higher rent.
A stately old man walked out the door of the customer center of the RPG Byty company of "coal baron" Zdenek Bakal, the largest private owner of rental apartments in the Czech Republic.
He was carrying a file with three new leases for three apartments: his own, his daughter's, and his son's, who is serving a sentence.
Deregulation has raised the rent for these three people.
Instead of paying 3500 the son will have to pay from next year for a 2+1 second-class apartment 4100 crowns.
"And there's no hot water and the heating runs on solid fuel", points to his son's new contract the man who has the power to sign.
"But I signed it anyway", he explains, angry and half-resigned.
The citizens' association of BytyOKD.cz, which described the new rental conditions as "immoral and indecent", advises tenants not to sign and wait until 7 December, when a notice will be published explaining the method to follow to claim.
But the man responds to this with a gesture.
"One says this, the other says that", with a frown.
The Ostrava region is becoming the laboratory of deregulation.
After the New Year, this is what most apartments in the Czech Republic are like, where the rents do not match the market price.
Aktualne.cz therefore decided to visit the "laboratory" personally.
The RPG waiting room in Havirovska Street is one of four in the Ostrava region and it is already full on Tuesday at 09:00 am.
Right next to the door is a security guard with a device to call customers.
A special button, "rent 2011", is turned on on the touchscreen.
One push and a piece of paper with a number on it comes out of the machine.
You don't have time to read your number "157" as your number is already starting to light up on the big screen under the roof of the waiting room.
In a split second, it's your turn.
After a short while,an old couple arrives to inquire about the rent, but the new rent does not seem to concern the people in the waiting room.
Most people came to deal with common problems like everywhere else - requests for repairs, insurance events and so on.
In the Ostrava region, people from over 44,000 apartments in the RPG portfolio have been receiving mail with new leases in their mailboxes since about mid-November.
RPG Byty offers them rent increases from 15 to 38 percent.
The special ticket office for new rents has been open to the public since 18 November.
"It's been working for almost a week, so it's still being tested", the clerk at the counter replies after a moment's hesitation when the customer introduces himself as a journalist.
The demolition and former miners' apartments in Bakal are a very sensitive local issue.
The Vice-President of the Parliament, Lubomir Zaoralek, from the Ostrava region of the Social Democrats, made a fairly strong statement about this before the elections and it is now in the local newspapers.
"20 years after them, I want a new floor".
"They didn't even change a fucking board in the toilet", the man relieves in the introduction.
However, according to the employees, it is mainly pensioners who come to make sure that they will receive a rebate on the new rent price if they sign now as promised by RPG in a special offer.
This is a rebate of half the amount of rent that other tenants who sign their new lease before 15 December will receive.
But the "deregulation" counter on Havirovaska Street is really not overwhelmed with questions.
"Of the 360 customers who came yesterday, only 40 to 50 came for rent", says the clerk.
And yet RPG provides both on its website and in its showcases individual rent interviews when needed.
If the parties disagree on the rent, an independent court will decide.
'This is not about threats but just about the only legitimate way to act legally,' RPG says on its website.
"This person will not go to court", one of the employees of RPG Byty thinks and the man in the street in front of the customer centre agrees.
"I have 13,000 crowns of pension and I have 5,000 crowns left to eat, I don't have enough to go to court", he said.
The employee suddenly feels uncomfortable.
"We'll see about that".
"Mr. Zaoralek in the media is asking that nobody sign and so people are waiting", she says.
The rental regulation in the Czech Republic ends at the beginning of 2011 and the increases, according to RPG Byty, are an economic necessity.
"And, moreover, the current rents still do not reach the level necessary for the simple maintenance of the housing fund", says Pavel Klimes, director of the residential portfolio of the company RPG Byty, who points out that it is precisely the neglect of the housing fund that makes the tenant angry is the main reason for the increase in rent.
However, in 5 years between 2005 and 2010 RPG was able to invest in apartments with rents 4 billion, in four years from 2011 to 2014 this should be 5.2 billion.
The large screen, however, hanging from the ceiling in front of the upholstered chairs in the Havirosvka Street waiting room, repeats some information in red.
'The rent increase in 2011 is 15 per cent and concerns no less than 31200 apartments or more than 90 per cent of RPG apartments.'
"And it will still be at most 7.50 Czech crowns per m2 per month", says the screen.
The 38 percent increase is only for 400 apartments in the RPG portfolio.
"In these cases, this is a really low increase of 19.66 CZK per m2", adds RPG.
Next year, the rent will remain the same for 2600 apartments.
RPG Byty promises that deregulation will not cause a radical but gradual increase over 4 to 8 years.
It adds other commitments: all the money from the rent increase (see graph) is returned to the apartments in the form of heating savings - new windows and heating.
Those who sign the rent increase agreement have priority.
The kindergarten is also part of the office, including the architects.
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch. Design.
No one could have expected that it would also house a mini-kindergarten with everything you need - colored walls, imaginative furniture, toys and finally a miniature playground on the terrace.
Since October last year, the children of Arch. design employees have been able to visit.
The architectural design firm Arch. Design. whose workshops have produced a large number of buildings in Brno, has been designing its mini-enterprise kindergarten since the first drafts of the Avriopoint building.
It employed about 90 people, mostly of childbearing age, and was concerned that women architects and project managers could return to work quickly.
Along with parttime employment contracts, kindergarten is a bonus offered to employees by Arch Design as part of its social programme.
This gives builders and architects the opportunity to combine demanding work with childcare.
Arch.Design employees themselves conceived the idea of this kindergarten and with the support of the management they were able to obtain a grant from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The mini-nursery school is financed by the European Social Fund through the operational programme for human resources and the State Budget of the Czech Republic.
The financing grants (CZK 2.8 million) enabled them to buy equipment and equipment and after two years to provide qualified staff and start-up.
After the use of the funding (two years) the company Arch. Design. has the obligation after 3 years to operate the mini kindergarten on its own funds.
The project took a year to prepare and the company Economy rating helped to apply for funding.
The children are cared for by qualified staff, with a nurse and a kindergarten teacher taking care of the children all day. Children can attend kindergarten without age limitation but are mostly over three years old.
As this is a "mini-kindergarten" there can only be 5 children present at a time, but during the day there are more who replace each other.
The school is flexible according to the needs of the parents and the children of all employees have the same right to use the school regardless of their hierarchical position.
Although it is an individual care and education, the mini-nursery programme is comparable to that for preschool education.
The children do not only play there but there is also quality education - from the beginning to the preparation for school, English is taught.
The classroom is equipped not only with imaginative toys and games but also with a computer that the children can use.
The presence of young children in society creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can check on their child at any time and not have the stress of being late to pick up the children at a school far from the parents' workplace.
So parents use their working time in the most productive way.
It is not surprising that a natural relationship of loyalty develops between employee and employer.
Arch.Design.s is thus among the companies that offer a preferential bonus for the recruitment of new employees and that are family-friendly and through this programme strengthens the marketing of HR.
The bone house still fascinates after 100 years.
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric sauropod, the stairs look like a dinosaur spine, and the balconies look like open fish mouths.
This is the case of the Casa Battlo in Barcelona, designed by architect Antoni Gaudí.
Because of its organic forms, the house has been nicknamed the Bone House by the locals.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stones, fragments of tiles and mosaics, a façade reminiscent of scales and everywhere curves, these are all typical of Antoni Gaudi's Art Nouveau.
The front of the house is unfolding its dream lines, its pleasant colors and textures that remind us of nature and animals.
On closer inspection, the geometry, rhythm and order are clearly thought out.
At night the facade of the house becomes even more dramatic and is lit in such a way as to enhance the impression of bright colors.
The winding and twisting of the forms also appears in the interiors with the same measure.
The wood is used to make waves for window frames, balustrades, door decorations, eyelets, and slats.
The house Battlo, which stands in the Eixample district in the Passeig de Gracia shopping street at number 43, was born from the construction of a house from 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
The reconstruction took two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, Joseph Battlo, a wealthy contractor, first insisted on demolishing the old building and building a brand new one but quickly accepted Gaudi's idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
But the idea of Casa Battlo as a multi-apartment house was not conceived by Gaudi alone.
The architect Josep Maria Jujol worked with him.
It was precisely from his project that the decorations for a representative apartment of the building's owner and the use of mosaic for the facade were born.
Other artists and designers also worked on the facade.
The joint work on the plans for the Casa Battlo house began with a successful cooperation between Jujol and Gaudi.
Jujol participated in the construction of Gaudi's house Casa Mila and the Park Guell in which there are other works by Gaudi.
The locals nicknamed the hot house right after it was finished because of its organic shapes, "the Bone House".
Others, because of the specific mechanism of opening the windows, have called it "the house that beats".
It is said that on top of the building there is a sword similar to that of Saint George, the patron saint of Catalonia.
Other sculptural elements of the building contain hidden religious motifs.
Gaudí conceived a unique central heating system for the house, with typical ventilation and chimneys.
Their 45-degree inclination seems odd.
During the creation Gaudi did not follow the building directives of the time and did not let himself be hindered by them.
At the beginning of the construction he obtained the building permit from the city, knowing, of course, that the data on the reconstruction plans were so vague that two years later during the completion the city council was horrified and asked for changes.
For example, the members of the city council were not happy that the construction piers were encroaching on the public sidewalk.
No change was made, but, on the contrary, only 15 days after the city appealed, Josep Battlo asked (and got satisfaction) for permission to rent the two highest floors.
The owner moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a common living room and on the third a room and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey house is divided by a staircase leading up to an independent roof terrace.
All the right angles and straight lines were cancelled by the basic elements of the reconstruction and replaced by curved walls.
Gaudi also worked on the modern concept of space linkage.
The common part can be completely connected by opening the doors of the living rooms and the high society can communicate comfortably or else limit the private space for more intimate conversations.
The house with Gaudi's reconstruction received in addition to new facades an untraditional roof and two additional floors.
Gaudi's play with light is also impressive, with blue and white glass tiles decorating the courtyard and the lighthouses.
The two-color set gives maximum light in all floors of the house.
All we had to do was to bet on the principle that white reflects more than dark, which absorbs the sun's rays.
The Casa Battlo, which was inscribed in 2005 on the UNESCO World Heritage List, is a place that everyone can visit.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and splendid apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to take this step in 2002 on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous designer.
They continued to visit as they saw that it was a lucrative business and they expanded the scope of visits to the common areas and the attic including the roof terraces.
The entrance to the monument is really cheap, at 16.50 euros, and students, retirees, groups and tourist cardholders get 20 percent off.
The sum is still above the entrance price of the other Gaudi buildings in the city.
If you want to feel the real atmosphere of the house with its fantastic turrets, you must quickly find a companion among the inhabitants of the building and visit the house completely.
How to choose a mattress and a pillow: women have different criteria than men.
No fancy frame, but rather the quality of the sleeping surface, so the mattress and the top make a real foundation for a good bed.
Of course, they must complement each other harmoniously to please a specific user.
The choice is made on the basis of several factors: weight, height, age, health and sex of the owner.
The type of interior in which the mattress and pillow are to be placed is also important.
Typical example?
For example, in a country house where you don't sleep all the time, latex mattresses are not appropriate because they "warm up" slowly.
They are also heavier than standard polyurethane mattresses.
It is necessary to turn them frequently.
If they also lack ventilation channels at the core and are also on a solid board, they retain moisture and may also form mould.
Habit is also a factor in the choice.
If you spend a lot of time abroad, where you often use very thick mattresses with a soft covering, you will not feel comfortable on a low, hard surface.
"That's how every hockey player who comes back from the NHL complains they can't sleep there".
"For their tired shoulders, feet and ribs, they needed mattresses with a softening layer of lazy foam".
"Such mattresses are also recommended for people with diabetes who have a nervous system disorder and thus do not take the 'information' of joints and skin well", explains Sylva Adamczikova, who specializes in upholstered furniture.
That is why, a few years ago, the mattress with lazy foam won over the hockey players and other customers.
"Today everything is going well, Tempur, the Italian Magnifex but also the Czech Tropico have suitable mattresses for example.
You don't have to be an NHL guy to appreciate a lazy foam.
This "miracle" simply works.
It optimizes its rigidity and shape according to the heat absorbed or adapts to your body's heat.
Nothing presses you, and you don't turn around in the middle of the night like you've been through a tough game.
You just sleep better.
Lazy foam also acts as a protection against scratches.
To choose the mattress according to your height, add the length of the feet, which is about 21/34 cm.
So a man and a woman who are 180cm tall need a bed 210/220cm.
The minimum width for each of the two beds should be 90 cm, or 180 cm in total.
For single beds, for example single beds, it is recommended to take at least 120 /140 cm.
It's convenient for visitors.
'However, there is a simple rule for the width of the bed: when lying on your back you should lay your hands comfortably with your elbows slightly bent.' Helena Prokopova, President of the Association of Mattress Hangers and Decorators, who has been working for several years on the issue of healthy sleep and the ergonomics of furniture and who teaches this in special schools.
For a double bed each needs its own mattress and pillow, so be careful, however, when buying to choose the mattress height.
Otherwise, you will have to raise the top to different heights, and this is not feasible on all bed frames.
Foam mattresses should be at least 14 cm high, spring mattresses at least 15 cm, of which at least three centimetres should be used for the form and aeration layer.
