The demand for devices to track people is growing among parents who want to monitor their children.
Fear for their children is leading more and more people to think about monitoring them through GPS.
The system, which was initially set up to search for cars, can also be used to track the movement of people and help in some cases, such as the case of the little girl Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is currently as big as a matchbox but will soon be the size of a watch.
The case of little Anicka moved many people and they began to look for ways to better protect their children.
Even if the price is to disrupt their privacy.
"We try to tell everyone that this is not spying but just another way to reduce the likelihood of another tragedy", says Petr Pilin of MAcro Weil, one of the suppliers of tracking devices on the Czech market.
"I admit that there may be cases of misuse of such devices, such as putting it in the bag of someone who is not aware, but I have not yet encountered such cases".
"Most people are customers who actually buy the product for safety reasons", adds Pilin.
He said children should always know what the "box" is used for and how to use it in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bockova points out that if a child does not feel like wearing this type of thing, he will get rid of it.
'And even the smallest can be very creative when it comes to getting rid of something when they don't want to be in control.'
"Mobile phones, which can cut themselves off like these tracking devices, have already caused parents to wait for long periods", says Bockova.
She said that the fact that this type of device could help in the event of an attack is highly questionable.
"If it is a premeditated kidnapping, the perpetrator will make sure that the child does not have an electronic device that can locate him".
"Right now, it's the phone".
"As soon as the tracking devices are developed, they (the criminals) will look for them too because the sale will be supported by an advertising campaign".
"In such cases the criminals will always be ahead of the police", says the psychologist.
She admits, however, that such devices can help in the case of unplanned abuse by a pedophile.
According to Robert Cech of RC Monitoring, a company that provides tracking services for both cars and people, having this type of device can help, even if it is destroyed in the event of an assault.
'The apparatus may be set so that it is in regular emission after a specified period.'
"In the event that the device is destroyed, the last position of the person concerned remains".
'More expensive devices also have an inclinometer that immediately indicates the position of the person who slipped and is in a lying position without moving,' says Cech.
He said that so-called smart mobile phones, which are equipped with a navigation system, can offer a comparable service after having formatted it with special prologue software.
The problem with current tracking systems is that they are either a device similar to those we wear in a matchbox-sized pendant or to the smallest telephone devices.
We can always lose them.
According to Pilina of the Macro Weil company, this is why tests are currently being conducted to make devices that resemble common digital watches.
"This will have the advantage that the potential assailant will not be able to recognize the tracking device".
"Or he will find out after a while, which will give the police a little more time", he adds.
Whether the tracking device is developed in the form of a bracelet or a pendant, it would still use the same technology as it does to track cars.
It is a combination of GPS positioning systems (commonly used in self-navigation) and a mobile phone function that alerts the vehicle's current position.
