Households will pay an extra 100 crowns a month for housing.
From January households will have to pay extra not only for all types of energy but also for water and sanitation, heating supplies and in some places rents will also increase.
From January onwards, families will have to draw up to 100 crowns more than they do now.
Electricity is up 4.6 percent, gas is up almost 2 percent, in some areas you will have to pay up to a tenth more for water supply and in many places central heating supplies will also be more expensive.
The increase in electricity for apartment households is expected to be around 100 crowns more per year than at present.
However, all suppliers have lowered electricity prices given the development which is sensitive to encouraging the manufacture of renewable energy, in particular photovoltaic cells.
The gas increases moderately but naturally at the time when people need it most for heating and therefore have the greatest consumption.
So we can also count about a hundred crowns more.
Although electricity and gas are increasing throughout the Czech Republic, the price change for central heating differs from city to city.
It is mainly the larger municipalities that plan the price increase.
For example, households in Pardubice or Hradec Kraloce will pay almost 50 crowns more per month for central heating from January, while families in Libérec will pay more than 1000 crowns per year.
For the inhabitants of Prague, a 9 percent increase in water and sanitation is being prepared in case the city raises infrastructure rents.
If the rent doesn't change, the Prague residents will pay an extra 6.8 percent.
The price in Prague will still be among the lowest in comparison with the whole country.
In northern Bohemia, where prices are already among the highest, water and sanitation are up 7.4 percent.
The prices of rent will increase considerably, for example, in the 450 thousand apartments rented from January onwards, i.e. at the end of the regulation.
For example, the company CPI Byty, which has almost 2500 apartments in Usti nad Labem, has decided to increase the number of apartments by up to 100 per cent.
Those who will not agree with the new rent increase will be brought to court by the company.
The regulated rents people pay in almost 300,000 apartments could increase next year by 10 percent.
