Two L-159s are in foreign hands for the first time in Spain.
Two L-159s out of five in total, for which the Ministry of Defence has traded Casa C-295M transport aircraft, took off Tuesday for Seville, Spain, where the aircraft manufacturer Casa-EADS is based.
This is the first time that such a device has become the property of someone other than the Czech army.
They have been abroad for exercises or demonstration flights.
These are the two-seat versions of the L-159T1 which were until now in service with the Czech Army and which were in flight condition.
The remaining aircraft are single-seat versions of the L-159.
They are currently stationed at Aero Vodochody and the commercial intermediary - the firm Omnipol - took them into account last week.
According to Jan Pejsek of the Defense Ministry's press department, the physical departure of the Vodochody planes is currently unknown.
'The L-159 single-seaters planned for exchange were taken from long-stored aircraft without causing additional costs or investment for the Ministry of Defence.'
"The L-159 T1 two-seaters have been exchanged in the state", said Pravo Pejsek.
He added that the army will not be left without two seats since the ministry signed in May 2009 with Aero Vodochody an agreement worth 200 million crowns for the conversion of four unused L-159 single-seaters into two two-seaters.
The army took delivery of the first aircraft in July, with the second one scheduled for delivery later this year.
According to Pejsek, EADS has committed itself to introducing the aircraft into the equipment of certain countries of the Alliance.
"The contract clearly states that the one who takes the L-159s into account is EADS and that they will be used for training pilots from NATO member countries".
