A longer index finger than the ring finger is a sign of low cancer risk
Men who have a thumb that's longer than the ring finger have a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday in the British magazine Cancer.
It may depend on the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our findings show that the relative length of the finger is a simple test of prostate cancer risk, particularly for men under 60", said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could thus help to determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, including in combination with genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as family health history, Eeles added.
During the period 1994-2009 she and her colleagues in Great Britain followed more than 1500 prostate cancer patients and at the same time nearly three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had the index finger of the right hand shorter than the ring finger.
They and 19 percent of those with the same length of fingers were found to have the same chance of prostate cancer.
For those with a longer index finger than the ring finger, however, the risk fell to 33 per cent, for men before the age of 60 the risk decrease was 87 per cent.
The ratio of the lengths of the two fingers - formed during the prenatal period - indicates, among other things, the different levels of sex hormones to which the child is exposed in the womb.
Less testosterone is a longer index.
Previous research had shown that testosterone is the key to prostate cancer.
Professor Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, told CTK that he was aware of the study but that he did not think the link between finger length and cancer had been "fully demonstrated".
