The two opposition candidates, Michel Martelly, a rapper, and Mirlande Manigat, a former first lady, withdrew their initial call for the vote to be declared void.
But there may be problems if Mr Célestin, who has little or no perceptible support among voters, is declared by the electoral authority as having reached the second round and reaches the second round.
With a cholera epidemic raging, and more than 1 million earthquake survivors still living in tents, there was a fear that participation would be limited.
In this case, many Haitians wanted to vote but were prevented from doing so because of disorganization.
Nearly 250,000 identity cards, required to vote, were not yet distributed shortly before the election.
The stakes are high.
Donors see the election of a popular and legitimate government as an important step in the reconstruction of Haiti.
And so, obviously, Haitians do it themselves.
The tip of the foot towards the center
Weeks after becoming a widow, Argentina's Cristina Fernández has enjoyed a surge of public sympathy that has increased her approval rating by 20 points to more than 50 percent, her highest level since being elected in 2007.
Yet whether this turns into a successful campaign for a second term in an election next year might depend on the choice of the visibly grieving Fernández, whether or not she will abandon the intransigence of her late husband, predecessor and former political partner, Néstor Kirchner.
And the signs are still confusing.
Mr Kirchner, who continued to manage economic policy even after his wife succeeded him as president, used to draw up budgets that underestimated tax revenues, economic growth and inflation.
This allowed the first couple to spend the extra income as they pleased.
Mrs Fernández's government lost its majority in Congress last year, on paper.
But the opposition is divided, and the situation has plunged into disarray following Mr Kirchner's death of a heart attack on 27 October.
Some of the dissident members of the ruling Peronist movement have joined Mrs Fernández.
But after chaotic sessions (where a lawmaker slapped one of his colleagues in the face and others accused the government of corruption), Congress doesn't have to approve the 2011 budget.
"I'm not going to argue", said the president.
Currently, the 2010 budget will be implemented next year, leaving the President even more leeway to spend as he pleases.
The economy is overheating to a large extent: it is likely to grow by almost 9% this year.
The official inflation rate is now 11.1%, but many private estimates and union wage claims put the figure at close to 30%.
Mr Kirchner, who took office in 2003 when Argentina feared an economic collapse, has made growth and poverty reduction a priority over inflation control.
It refused to deal with the IMF, harassed the private sector and purged INDEC, the statistical office, which had falsified official inflation statistics.
Can Mrs Fernández now moderate these policies?
It called for talks between private enterprises and trade union leaders.
And his officials say they want to limit next year's wage increases to 18 percent.
The economy was stimulated by high world prices of Argentina's agricultural exports.
But inflation eroded the growth stimulus following a sharp devaluation in 2002.
Perhaps this is why Mrs Fernández is showing signs of wanting to re-establish Argentina's financial relations with the rest of the world.
This year the government reached an agreement with the bondholders who had refused a previous forced restructuring of the debt for which Argentina had not settled its maturities in 2001.
Now Ms Fernández seems to be edging towards an agreement with creditor governments grouped in the Paris Club, to which it owes some $6.7 billion.
The Kirchners have always insisted that this could not involve IMF surveillance, as is customary.
But last month, Amado Boudou, the Minister of Economy, announced that the Fund would provide "technical assistance" to design a new national consumer price index, which sounds like a prelude to the consolidation of the INDEC.
It is unclear whether Mrs Fernández wants to remain in politics beyond the end of her term, now that her husband is no longer with her.
If it does, it needs to win the support of the middle class, among whom Kirchnerism is very prevalent.
When Argentinians return from their summer holidays in March, the wave of sympathy for her will have receded.
If she wants to win another election, she'll have to decide whether or not to quietly repudiate many of her husband's policies.
Half an hour to China
Taiwanese voters have moved towards a kind of closer union with the mainland.
What does Taiwan think of its big brother on the other side of the strait?
More than 7.5 million voters turned out on November 27, or 70 percent of eligible voters, to elect mayors and city councillors in five urban districts, as part of what is considered a general assessment by President Ma Ying-jeou.
Mr. Ma himself has become a substitute for feelings towards the continent, having forged innovative business ties, including a partial free trade pact, in the biggest reorganization of relations with China proper since 1949.
Mr. Ma passed the test, but just like that.
Although his Kuomintang (KMT) party won three of the five mayoral seats, he failed to win a majority of the votes.
Instead, the Democratic Progressive Party (DPP), which leaned towards full independence for Taiwan, won nearly 50% of all votes for the 45% KMT.
If this was a presidential election, Mr. Ma would be in trouble.
Since he was elected two years ago, his party's vote share has fallen by about 8%.
For the first time, the DPP attracted voters, even with the KMT in the municipal councils.
The event unveiled most of the main themes of the Taiwanese election, including noisy campaign trucks and mass rally flags with girls dancing in minimal attire.
A mysterious forced assassination attempt was also perpetrated.
Sean Lien, son of Lien Chan, honorary chairman of the KMT, conducted a campaign tour for a KMT candidate on the eve of the election.
A man in the crowd shot young Mr. Lien, just across the face, injuring him and killing a passerby.
Oddly, it was not determined whether the shooter intended to harm Mr. Lien or settle a dispute with the candidate.
Anyway, says Tsai Ing-wen, the leader of the PDP, the murder had consequences on the election by directing suspicion on the DPP and turning voters towards the KMT.
Perhaps the biggest winner of the election was China.
It was striking how absent the question of the continental part itself was.
Instead, the candidates played with plans for public housing and job creation.
Taiwan usually enjoys de facto independence and hates the military threat from China.
Thus, the KMT tends to avoid showing off its ties with the Beijing government.
But this time, the DPP also refrained from stirring up anti-Chinese sentiment.
This is in response to a new awareness that Chinese companies are essential to Taiwan's economic survival.
Mr Ma, for his part, demanded confirmation as to whether his policy towards China was acceptable to the Taiwanese majority.
It can be expected that the Beijing government will continue to provide trade facilities, in line with its strategy to lure Taiwan back into the fold.
China has sent a negotiator to Taipei to organize a summit on investment protection and medical cooperation.
It would also like to see political integration, but let us start at the beginning.
It's better to wait for that after the 2012 presidential election.
The DPP has reinvented itself anyway.
Two years ago, it was in bad shape when its former leader, Chen Shui-bian, was sent to prison on corruption charges.
President from 2000 to 2008, he was a provocateur in favour of explicit independence.
But a new generation of moderates has emerged under Ms Tsai's leadership and the PDP is doing its best to attract professionals and young people.
Ms. Tsai was hailed as a DPP presidential candidate, as was Su Tseng-chang, who served under Mr. Chen.
Their party is doing its best to show that it too can engage with Beijing.
Ms Tsai announced plans for a panel of experts to act as a point of contact between the DPP and China, provided that their talks can take place without preconditions.
Ms. Tsai tells Taiwanese audiences that her party presents a "trustworthy alternative" to Mr. Ma's hasty approach to China.
Mr. Chen seems exasperated by this change.
In a statement released from his cell, he said that the PDP candidates would have achieved better results if they had insisted that Taiwan is a separate country.
He even ordered Mr. Su, a pragmatic, not to run for president.
Even without Mr. Chen's intervention, the DPP will have a hard time choosing between its potential candidates.
The KMT needs to do an introspection of itself.
Mr. Ma's ratings were low; despite skyrocketing economic growth, KMT candidates did not want to campaign with him.
Much of its unpopularity seems to be due to unemployment and the widening gap between rich and poor.
A KMT spokesman says his office and local stations will be reshuffled.
The good results of the PDP suggest that Taiwan's support for rapprochement is limited.
At the same time, most Taiwanese see economic integration with China as inevitable.
According to prominent columnist Antonio Chiang, "the point of no return has already passed".
Grammy nominations: Jazz singer Esperanza Spalding is a surprise selection in the category of "best new artist"
It's a request from the president, and the people are required to know about it.
Esperanza Spalding, the 26-year-old jazz bassist and singer handpicked by President Obama to perform at his 2009 Nobel Peace Prize ceremony, marked one of the surprises at this year's Grammy Awards with a sweeping nomination in the "Best New Artist" category.
Considering that Spalding has been a well-known figure in the jazz scene since her 2008 album, "Esperanza", the nomination remains a bit of a mystery but is consistent with the Grammy Awards rules that an artist must not release more than three albums before recording; this "establishes the public identity of that artist".
Her ambitious 2010 album, "Chamber Music Society", certainly marked a step forward and, given her slightly engaging vocal style, skilled hand of pop and funk and Latin influences, it is possible to draw at least a dotted line at Spalding compared to the lightning success of Norah Jones in 2003, the closest equivalent for Grammy voters considering jazz productions in this category in recent years.
Elsewhere, Grammy voters rightly honored Vijay Iyer Trio's "Historicity" in the "instrumental album" category, a nod to a refreshing thrill from a recording that was one of last year's top favorites.
Among these Iyer, "Moody 4B" by veteran saxophonist James Moody and "Positootly" by keyboardist John Beasley will be in competition.
Shorty, a New Orleans-based trombone favorite with a raucous voice and a frequent guest on HBO's "Treme", was honored in the contemporary jazz category; which also leans heavily toward certain fusion with albums by Stanley Clarke, John McLaughlin and Jeff Lorber.
Steampunk-familiar Wild Darcy James Argue's Secret Society won some well-deserved recognition in the big ensemble category; competing with the rich chamber-jazz of the Billy Childs Ensemble and the ever-adventurous Dave Holland whose live octet's "Pathways" album was a fine example of this bassist's democratic hand as a bandleader.
Grammy nominations: Michael Daugherty and Steve Mackey lead in the classical categories
The classic nominations for the 53rd annual Grammy Awards feature a mix of landscapes from musicians and composers from around the world.
The nominees include Michael Daugherty's "Deus Ex Machina" for piano and orchestra, with five "yeses"; and Steve Mackey's "Dreamhouse", an electric orchestral work, with three "yeses".
Among the nominees with ties to Southern California is Estonian composer Arvo Pärt for his Symphony No. 4, "Los Angeles", a work that was commissioned by the Los Angeles Philharmonic Orchestra and opened the Walt Disney Concert Hall in 2009.
The Madolin Concerto by Los Angeles-based composer Avner Dorman is also in the running for an award.
The classical nominations are divided into 13 categories covering orchestral, opera, choral and solo recordings.
A category for classic producer of the year features five nominees: Blanton Alspaugh, David Frost, Tim Handley, Marina and Victor Ledin and James Mallinson.
Nominations for the classical album include Bruckner's Symphonies Nos. 3 and 4 from the Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra; "Deus Ex Machina" and "Metropolis Symphony" from Daugherty from the Nashville Symphony Orchestra; "Dreamhouse" from Steven Mackey from the Boston Modern Orchestra Project and Synergy Vocals; "Sacrificium - the Art of the Castrati" featuring various artists; and Verdi's "Requiem" from the Chicago Symphony Orchestra and Chorus.
In the opera category, the nominees are "Lulu" by Berg of the Royal Opera House Orchestra, "Marc Antonio e Cleopatra" by Adolf Hasse of the Ars Lyrica Houston; "L'Amour de Loin" by Kaija Saariaho of the Deutsches Symphonie-Orchester Berlin; "The Enchanted Wanderer" by Rodion Shchedrin of the Orchestra and Choir of the Mariinsky Theatre; and "Ivanhoe" by Arthur Sullivan of the BBC National Orchestra of Wales.
The composers who are in place for the Grammy Awards for contemporary composition include Pärt for Symphony No. 4, Daugherty for "Deus Ex Machina", Hans Werner Henze for "Appassionately Plus", Magnus Lindberg for "Graffiti" and Shchedrin for "The Wanderer Enchanted".
Pärt's Symphony No. 4 premiered at Disney Hall in January 2009 in a performance recorded by the Los Angeles Philharmonic Orchestra, conducted by Esa-Pekka Salonen.
The approximately 30-minute piece is nicknamed "Los Angeles" and is dedicated to the former oil tycoon Mikhail Khodorkovsky, imprisoned in Russia.
Dorman's "Mandolin Concerto" was nominated for its instrumental performance as soloist with an orchestra.
The Los Angeles composer said he wrote the 15-minute piece specifically for mandolin player Avi Avital, who performed the concerto with the New York-based Metropolis Ensemble.
"I wrote it using sounds from the Middle East and a lot of North African rhythms and scales", Dorman said in a telephone interview.
85-year-old conductor Pierre Boulez has received a nomination in the orchestral performance category for his performance of the Chicago Symphony Orchestra in a recording of Stravinsky's works.
Among the instrumental soloists who received a nomination were the pianists Nelson Freire and Marc-André Hamelin; the organist Paul Jacobs; the violinist Julia Fischer; and the harpist Sarah Schuster Ericsson.
This year, only soloists are nominated: Anne Sofie Von Otter, Cecilia Bartoli, Lucie Duchonová, Vivica Genaux and Measha Brueggergosman.
In the classical mix category, soprano Jessye Norman was nominated for her recording of "Roots: My Life, My Song".
