A microbe that tolerates arsenic raises the possibility of new life forms on Earth, or elsewhere.
The discovery of a strange bacterium, which can use arsenic as one of its nutrients, opens the field to finding new life forms on Earth and perhaps beyond.
Although researchers have discovered the unusual bacteria here on Earth, they say it shows that life has possibilities beyond the major elements that have been considered essential.
"This organism has a double capacity".
"It can grow either with phosphorus or with arsenic".
"That is why it is so special, even though it is far from being a truly 'foreign' life form", commented Paul Davies C. W. of Arizona State University, co-author of the report in Thursday's online edition of the journal Science.
For a long time, six major elements have been considered essential for life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus, and sulfur.
But researchers have discovered that the bacteria, discovered in Mono Lake, California, is able to continue to grow after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
"We wonder what is still possible", said Ariel Anbar D. of Arizona State University, a co-author of the report.
The discovery is important in the search for life beyond Earth because researchers need to be able to recognize life, to know what life looks like, Anbar says.
The study focuses on a microbe found on Earth.
However, the announcement of a press conference to discuss the discovery, which did not release details of the discovery, generated widespread speculation on the Internet that the report might reveal the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
It didn't.
The discovery "shows that in other planetary environments organisms might be able to use other elements to drive biochemistry and that the 'standard' set of elements we consider absolutely necessary for life may not be fixed", commented Charles Cockell, professor at the Institute for Planetary and Space Scientific Research, Open University, Milton Keynes, United Kingdom.
Cockell wasn't part of the research team.
"This work is novel because it shows the substitution of one element for another in basic biochemistry and biochemical structure", added Cockell.
It wasn't a chance discovery.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Institute of Astrology, who led the study, chose Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, so she speculated that a microbe exposed to both substances might be able to substitute for one another.
"Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is very similar to that of phosphorus".
"As a result, organisms have difficulty distinguishing these elements separately".
"But arsenic is different enough that it does not work exactly like phosphorus; it gets inside and, in a way, blocks the work of our biochemical machine", explained Anbar.
The researchers collected the bacterium known as GFAJ-1 and exposed it to increasing concentrations of arsenic, which allowed it to adapt and grow.
The microbe grows better with phosphorus, but the fact that it can live with arsenic instead raises the possibility that a form of life using arsenic could occur naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more abundant.
Jamie S. Foster, assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said that the idea that arsenic could be replaced by phosphorus was not new; but nothing has ever shown that it could work.
Arsenic was more common in the early days of the earth, she says, so researchers hypothesized that early life forms could have used it.
This suggests that there could be other ways life formed, not just the way life on Earth formed in the beginning", said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was funded by NASA, the Department of Energy, and the National Institutes of Health.
The last two stolen show dogs were found in Compton.
The other two of four show dogs stolen from outside a motel in Bellflower have been found, Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department announced Thursday.
The four show dogs - two akitas and two Welsh pembrokes - were reported missing Tuesday when someone stole the Chevrolet Express van they had spent the night in outside a Bellflower Motel 6, authorities said.
Two of the dogs were recovered Wednesday afternoon and the other two were found late Wednesday evening, Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department spokesman Steve Whitmore told the AP.
"The good news is the dogs are fine", says Whitmore.
"They're in good shape".
"They have been returned to their rightful owners".
Whitmore declined to say exactly where the dogs had been found, in what neighborhood, or what the circumstances of their discovery were.
"An investigation is underway".
"We don't want to say it", said Whitmore.
"We follow orders".
The dogs' owners, Kristina Rickard and David Peek, were unable to be reached for comment Thursday.
They were reunited with their two Akitas Wednesday afternoon at the county animal shelter in Downey.
Sheriff's deputies found the van and the two dogs separately in Compton.
The Akitas - a 3-year-old male and a 10-month-old female - were safe, authorities said.
But Bunny and Peter, the corgis Rickard and Peek had planned to show at regional contests this week on behalf of Japanese dog owners, were missing until their discovery Wednesday night.
Peek and Rickard, who live in Redding, are in town this weekend for the Long Beach AKC/Eukanuba National Championship, where they're expected to present Trace.
The other dogs were expected to compete in other events scheduled in the days leading up to the "AKC/Eukanuba" exhibition, Peek told the Times on Wednesday.
Southern California is one of the stops on the couple's nearly month-long dog exhibition tour.
Monday night, Peek and Rickard checked the motel.
They often stay in motels and park their van outside, right by their bedroom window.
They took three other dogs - a Boxer puppy, a Parson Russell terrier, and a Breton Spaniel - and they stayed with them in the motel room.
But they left the Akitas and the thicker-fur corgis in the van where it would be cooler.
They opened the windows a little bit, so the dogs could get some fresh air.
Peek and Rickard reported the van stolen at 6:00 Tuesday.
Peek said they'd offer a reward to anyone who could lead them to the corgis, with a microchip implanted to identify them.
