The lion's ready to blush again, the restructuring of MGM is waiting for the final green light from the court
After 18 months of turmoil and uncertainty, MGM finally got the green light to start over.
A New York bankruptcy judge on Thursday officially praised the creditors' "pre-packaged" plan to write off about $5 billion in debt, paving the way for the 86-year-old entertainment company to focus its efforts on producing and distributing movies and television shows.
With Thursday's decision that the plan meets the requirements of the U.S. bankruptcy code, there are no legal obstacles left for MGM to get back on the air under the tutelage of Entertainment Spyglass founders Gary Barber and Roger Birnbaum, who will become the general managers of what will be a lightweight studio.
The staff will be reduced to about 320 out of 400 initially.
MGM will not actually emerge from Chapter 11 until JPMorgan Chase has entered into a $500 million credit facility to finance MGM's new operations and productions.
It is currently licensed by the investment bank, which is itself facing a $75 million funding challenge, and is expected to be funded by mid-December.
The restructuring process of the studio began in May 2009 when the investment bank Moelis & Co. was hired to advise management on how to invest its finances as it could not afford to pay the interest of $300 million per year.
In August, the CEO, Harry Sloan, was replaced by Stephen Cooper, a former Enron CEO and recovery expert known for his work at Krispy Kreme Doughnuts.
Moelis and Cooper's attempts to resolve MGM's financial difficulties and satisfy the studio's more than 140 creditors took much longer than expected.
After several months of discussions, the parties agreed, at the end of 2009, to sell the company.
However, the auction attracted few bidders, none of whom were willing to pay the additional 2 billion that the creditors were looking for.
In the spring of this year, it was time to do it all over again as the MGM team had begun work on a restructuring plan which, after months of disagreements and internal debate, was finally approved by the creditors at the end of October.
When MGM officially emerges from bankruptcy in the following weeks, the Moelis and Cooper companies receive multi-million dollar bonuses for their work.
Moelis & Co., which has already received $1.2 million, will receive a payment of $9.5 million.
Cooper's companies, which have raised $375,000 a month for their corporate management services, will receive a "success bonus" of $4 million.
Barber and Birnbaum plan to revive the production of MGM, which has only released one film this year, and put together an annual list of seven or eight films that would be released starting in 2012.
They also intend to co-finance two films based on "The Hobbit", with Warner Bros.
The studio is to take out a separate loan of between $265 million and $275 million to finance its share in these two films, which are to be directed by Peter Jackson.
Investor Carl Icahn, who owns about 18% of MGM's debt, has attempted to merge the studio with Lions Gate Entertainment, where he is the majority shareholder.
However, recent discussions between the two companies have not resulted in an agreement.
Tech toys to keep your budget balanced gifts
While the leading candidate for this year's most wonderful toy is the iPad, followed, perhaps, by Microsoft's Kinect video game system, both can make a significant dent in your gift budget.
Consider that for the price of an iPad, you can buy five BMX bikes for $99, and a Kinect game costs the same as 10 classic pearl jump strings, or about 48 boxes of Play-Doh.
But there are ways to keep your gift budget in balance.
I recently visited three national toy retailers -- Wal-Mart, Toys "R" Us, and BJ's Wholesale Club -- to see which electronic toys I could buy for less than $80.
Clearly Moore's Law has evolved, this year's technological toy is likely to have more power; while still costing the same price if not a little less, compared to last year.
Also, while there are usually fewer new toys associated with websites, two of the best-known of this type, Webkinz and Club Penguin, have more offerings.
And button-battery toys are on the rise, as are rechargeable battery toys.
Here are some suggestions.
(All prices are from Toys "R" Us, unless otherwise noted.)
Sing-a-ma-jigs (Mattel, $13 for 3 and up) are stuffed toys the size of a guinea pig that sing a note when you press on their belly.
One push is equal to one note, and a second push composes a song.
If you buy several, they'll sing in harmony.
Be careful, once you start pressing, you can't stop.
For combining singing with dancing, Dance Mickey Star (Fisher-Price, $60 for 2 years and older) is the best choice.
Inspired by last year's Elmo Live technology, the 14-inch animatronic doll plays role-playing games like Simon Says and can do the moon dance with its innovative articulated feet with wheel-locking.
The children who tried the toy used Mickey as a dance instructor while their parents complained of a lack of volume control.
