He's back (Hasbro/Playskool, $40 for 3+), with a backpack filled with quiz game cards designed to turn a car ride into a session with self-correction and a valve workbook.
If you're wary of your child holding your smartphone, here are three self-contained alternatives.
VTech's Mobigo ($60, for ages 3-8) is the cheapest and easiest to use, with a qwerty keyboard, although games don't educate as effectively as the Explorer Leapster ($70, for ages 3-12); it is the first major revision of the Leapster line, with a newer and brighter screen.
No versions are compatible with the old cartridges.
The Fisher-Price iXL ($90, for 3-7 year olds) uses an iTunes-like system to offer games and e-books and has an SD card slot that allows viewing family photos.
Finally, Scrabble Flash ($30 Hasbro for ages 8 and up) is a set of five blocks barely larger than a matchbox, each with its own LED display.
The goal is to form words by putting the blocks in a row before time runs out, which is ideal for an impromptu spelling bee.
Increasingly, toys have some sort of online connection.
Based on their presence in toy stores alone, the two biggest are Webkinz and Club Penguin.
To buy your child a Penguin Club pet online, for example, you can get a Penguin Disney Club 2"Mix 'N Match Figure Pack, $5 (for ages 6 to 12) that includes a coin marked with a hidden code.
When you redeem the code online, your child gets enough Club Penguin store credits for two items to choose from.
It could be roller skates or a Puffle toy pet.
Slightly larger than the hair on the end of your toothbrush, the Hexbug Nano ($10, for 5 years and older) is the latest button-battery micro-robot.
The fake bestiole is moving rapidly on 12 vibrating silicone patches in random directions.
It's fun to do a maze of blocks to see if she can find her way through.
It's also solid.
Our dog survived a fall from the kitchen table and even a brief pass in the dog's mouth.
Bringing a softer side to China's law enforcement
Tang Shenbin was walking around a city square like a city sergeant in training by severely inspecting his nervous loads, issuing low-key orders with a military authority.
He wanted the female members of chengguan - imposing law enforcement officials in China, feared and despised for their arbitrary repression and penchant for violence - to convey a certain impression to a set of spectators.
"Stay up straight!"
"Be Sharp!"
He said, "Show them what pretty girls look like".
Four girls, barely past their teenage years, wearing white gloves, identical olive-colored jackets and trousers, were staring at the scene.
Four pairs of black heels, aligned with the rule.
Four neat hats perfectly perched on top of hair tied by a blue and white striped knot.
"Personally, I think they have an average appearance", said Mr. Tang, contemptuously.
"The models are nice".
Several governments have tried to refresh the image of China's urban inspectors.
One city required all new recruits to have a college degree.
Guangdong province has traded the grey-green uniforms for a supposedly more engaging blue.
Wuhan, in central China, has replaced the blindfold with the strong one: in 2009, a report reported that 50 officers surrounded an uncontrollable snack cart, staring at it with a black eye for half an hour, until the smuggler packed his things and left.
Xindu, an urban district of 680,000 people in Chengdu, chose to do a major image surgery.
Since 2003, the district has supplemented its urban street police force with 13 women, specially selected for their looks, their gauntlet and their young age.
The idea is to give the police a softer, more feminine side.
Unfortunately, even Scarlett Johansson might have a hard time getting a look at this underground urban Chinese brigade.
And for good reason, critics will say.
Unlike the police, these officers are only authorised to enforce municipal ordinances by imposing fines or other administrative sanctions.
But the Chinese media portray the news as a different reality.
In January 2008, inspectors in Hubei province beat to death an observer after he used his mobile phone to film them dispersing a protest against a landfill.
Last year, a training manual for Beijing inspectors was stolen and posted online, describing how to effectively defeat criminals without shedding blood.
This year in Shanghai, a watermelon smuggler was left with a brain injury after a fight with five officers.
A violent video game, available for download, shows Chinese detectives trained to assault street vendors.
"Chengguan has marked the government", lamented China Daily, a national publication, last year, after an eleventh controversy over tactics.
The paper called for a "genuine clean-up".
Skeptics say that approach is far from it.
After the district announced in October that it was recruiting eight new female recruits, an editorial in The Beijing Evening News questioned whether the women had real jobs or were just tourist entertainment.
The answer seems to be a little of both.
The district's announcement required female candidates, ages 18 to 22, to have a good figure and "the five facial features in the right order".
They must be taller than the average, or about five feet, two and a half inches.
Retirement at 26 is compulsory.
Officers said the work was too physically demanding for women over 25.
"It's their image that's important", one district official told the quasi-government website Rednet.com.
"First, the candidates' external qualities will determine whether they are suitable; these are height, weight, facial features, etc".
Then there's the temperament and the "inner qualities".
Chengguan women are like flower pots, he said, adding: "In addition to being pots, they will have other responsibilities.
Zheng Lihua, deputy director of the city district management office, does not agree with this description.
But he noted that height requirements were the standard standard in many Chinese job offers for both sexes.
This is the case for the requirement concerning the order of facial features.
What that means is a matter of debate among the Chinese.
Of course, disabled or disfigured people do not have to apply.
"We cannot let a lame person or a hussy come to serve here", said Mr. Zheng.
"It wouldn't give a good impression".
