The prosecutors will not charge Senator Ensign.
Justice Department prosecutors have dropped criminal charges against Senator John Ensign stemming from a case involving a former campaign aide and his efforts to get a lobbying job for the woman's husband, the senator's lawyers announced Wednesday.
The decision ends the most serious legal threat facing Mr. Ensign, the Nevada Republican who was considered a possible Republican presidential candidate in 2012 until the scandal surrounding his case made national headlines last year and hurt his career.
Mr. Ensign's office said it was "very happy" with the decision, the result of a year-long investigation.
The senator could still be subject to disciplinary action by the Senate Ethics Committee.
Mr. Ensign's lawyers said the Justice Department had "informed that Senator Ensign was no longer under investigation and that he did not intend to maintain any charges against him in this case".
The Ministry of Justice refrained from commenting on this matter.
The announcement came as a surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Justice Department, who said there would be significant evidence indicating that Mr. Ensign had conspired to violate a federal criminal prohibition on lobbying.
Interviews, emails, and other documents, first released in October 2009 in the New York Times, indicated that Mr. Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, get a lucrative lobbying job to gain the silence of Mr. Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the senator's affair with her.
Mrs. Hampton once served as treasurer on an Ensign campaign.
Mr. Ensign contacted a number of political funders to find work for Mr. Hampton and then defended their rights after they hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them; according to the documents and interviews.
Since Mr. Hampton had recently been an employee of Mr. Ensign, he was forbidden by law for one year from lobbying his former employer or the Senate as a whole.
Ethics experts argued that the unusual agreement between Mr. Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were close friends before the case, appeared to contradict the so-called lobbying revolving door ban.
From the evidence that has been released, "there appears to be prima facie evidence of a conspiracy to violate and substantial violation of the revolving door law", said Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in defending clients of a government investigation.
Although the department's judge declined to explain the reasoning that led to the decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said the department appeared wary of political prosecutions after a number of high-level setbacks by its public integrity section, including the decision last year to drop prosecutions against former Senator Ted Stevens on charges of misprision of justice.
Federal prosecutors are clearly afraid to take up arms, said Melanie Sloan, executive director of Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, a advocacy group that has received several complaints against Mr. Ensign in the case.
"This basically means high-ranking government officials can now assume the laws don't apply to them", she added.
Paul Coggins, Mr. Ensign's lead attorney, said in an interview that he received a phone call from a Justice Department prosecutor on Monday and a follow-up the next day, telling him that the department was not looking for charges against his client.
Mr. Ensign's legal team had cooperated with prosecutors in trying to persuade them that the senator, as his office reaffirmed in a statement Wednesday, "had acted in accordance with the law".
Mr. Coggins refused to specify the legal arguments he had made to the prosecution.
"I'm not comfortable going into the details of my discussions with the Justice Department, except to say that we think they made the right decision", he said.
Last month, the Federal Election Commission decided to drop an investigation following an independent complaint by the ethics group, arguing that the $96,000 payment by Mr. Ensign's parents to the Hamptons violated federal election law.
The election commission said they didn't have enough evidence to prove the money was anything but a gift.
NV Energy, a major Nevada corporation that has long supported the senator, is a company that Mr. Ensign helped Mr. Hampton find lobbying work for.
An email sent in December 2008 showed that, after the company welcomed Mr. Hampton as a lobbyist, Mr. Ensign's chief of staff, John Lopez, contacted Mr. Hampton and told him that he was "marshalling" the Home Office on a contentious issue.
Mr. Ensign also attended a lunch with Mr. Hampton and another Nevada customer, Allegiant Air, and he asked the Secretary of Transportation to schedule a meeting on behalf of the airline after engaging Mr. Hampton to lobby.
When news of the case surfaced last year, Mr. Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned as the Republican leader of the Senate's fourth-tier.
After keeping a low profile for several months, Mr. Ensign announced two weeks ago that he intends to run for a third term in the Senate.
In announcing that Mr. Ensign was no longer the target of a criminal investigation, his spokeswoman, Jennifer Cooper, said the senator hoped that the ethics committee would quickly follow the Justice Department's lead and end his investigation.
Senator Ensign looks forward to continuing his hard work on behalf of the people of Nevada, she said.
