About half a dozen of them were tapping away in the courtroom rows.
They were tweeting horrible testimony every minute.
In the end, the defense said there were over 140,000 messages about the rape trial and the children tied to their beds in a house that was burned down.
On Thursday, the widely-watched trial of Steven J. Hayes, who was convicted of the murder of three members of the Cheshire family in Connecticut, is expected to lead to a formal end where the judge would impose the death penalty, voted on by the jury.
But Mr. Hayes' lawyers have already filed evidence in court that outlines appeal arguments that could occupy the courts for years.
What is provocative is that the intense reporting on the trial - as well as the widespread and widespread use of Twitter by journalists - created a "circus atmosphere", a saturation so widespread and instantaneous with incendiary details that the jury was mis-influenced by the public's passions.
The request could prompt appeal judges to debate whether new technologies require new rules in the courtroom.
"I experienced this in this trial, and I think there is a real danger that the introduction of new technology into the courtroom is a violation of the right to a fair trial", said Thomas J. Ullmann, counsel for Mr. Hayes, the lead counsel.
Trial judge Jon C. Bleue of the state Superior Court laconically rejected the claims in last week's ruling, saying the media was "carefully controlled" and there was no evidence that the jury was driven by passion.
But that does not seem to be the final word on the matter.
The appeal courts have recognized for decades that media coverage of high-profile cases can raise questions about the fairness of a trial.
In a landmark 1966 ruling, the U.S. Supreme Court overturned the conviction of Cleveland osteopath Dr. Sam Sheppard for the murder of his wife, arguing in its decision that there was a "carnival atmosphere at trial" because of the media.
The crime is considered by some to have been the inspiration for the television show and film "The Fugitive".
Some lawyers have said that the appeals courts seized to review Mr. Hayes' conviction half a century later may be curious given the argument that new rules might be needed to manage the means of communication in courtrooms, unimaginable at the time of Dr. Sheppard's case.
"There is general reason to be concerned about the impact of new media" on large-scale trials, said John J. Donohue III, a professor at Stanford Law School who studied the death penalty in Connecticut and wrote a report that it was arbitrarily enforced.
Professor Donohue says that some appeal judges might be intrigued by the idea that limiting instant communication from courtrooms could allow for fairer trials.
The Twitter case is just one of many described by Mr. Hayes' lawyers, which could be discussed for years, delaying the execution.
The defense lawyers also claim, for example, that Mr. Hayes suffered harm when Blue J. refused to allow them to test the reactions of potential jurors by showing them macabre photos of crime scenes during jury selection.
Some of the jurors said they were horrified by the photos of the victims, Jennifer Hawke-Petit, 48, and her daughters, Hayley, 17, and Michaela, 11.
The defense lawyers say they will also challenge the constitutionality of the death penalty and will argue that the judge unfairly dismissed one of the jurors, who had been critical of prosecutors, and that he unfairly pressured for a verdict by making the unusual decision to have the jury deliberate over a weekend.
The jurors were not sequestered.
But their arguments about the effect of the intense media coverage of the trial may be the biggest source of interest.
They noted in a challenge to the verdict, filed last month, that the case dominated the media scene in Connecticut and was discussed during the election campaign by candidates for governor and U.S. Senate.
They maintained that the computer media kept fanning the flames of the case.
"The daily twittering of media, cameras, and reporters outside the courthouse", the lawyers wrote, "was unlike anything seen before here in New Haven, and perhaps even nationwide".
Their focus on the coverage of the Twitter system is controversial.
In interviews, some journalists said that the claim that snapshots were more incendiary than the slower-delivered releases was a Luddite view that would impoverish the Court's policy governing media coverage of future trials.
But some lawyers said that the appeal courts were often attracted by the arguments that social and technological change required adjustment by the courts.
Mr. Hayes' lawyers insist on this claim.
In their filing, they refer to the 1966 Supreme Court decision that overturned Dr. Sheppard's conviction because of media coverage of the trial and they made it clear that they would invoke the need for new rules for new media.
"This case", they wrote, "represents the case of Sheppard v. Maxwell of the 21st century".
Can civility bring the divides closer?
After a campaign marked by inveteration and negativity, a minimum of civility has erupted in Washington this week.
Is this a sign of a real two-party cooperation going forward or an illusory moment before the rapid return to partisan struggle in the capital?
Tuesday's meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders produced no breakthrough on the big issues that must be addressed during the "Lumpy Duck" session.
But obviously, at least there was a polite discussion about the differences between the two parties as well as the recognition of their shared responsibilities in governing, rather than another episode where each side wanted to score points.
The public meeting of the Chairman's deficit committee on Wednesday was just as civilized, despite the political differences that remain between the members.
It seems clear that the close interaction of several months has created a mutual respect that transcends the ideological divide; but which, however, still divides the members.
This is hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Both sides are now in a period of mutual testing and testing in order to obtain signs of cooperation and compromise, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and voter patience for a renewed partisan war.
So the Tuesday meeting and subsequent comments from participants revealed a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too great and too deep to suggest a rapid change in the climate that has existed over the last two years.
Whether it's taxes, spending, health care or rights, the two sides are miles apart.
Yet the November election had moderated Washington, at least in the short term.
"There's no doubt that things have changed in tone", said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now with the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
"It's inevitable after the election.
Elections stir up partisan passions and then they fade away.
That's good".
On some issues, including the one on the agenda of the lame duck session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush's tax cuts are due to expire at the end of the year, and nobody is in favour of that.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve part or all of it, either permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, a compromise is possible on the extension of unemployment benefits, if only because the Republicans cannot afford to give the impression that they are in favour of tax cuts for the rich, while denying unemployment benefits to unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting at the White House, more optimism is looming over a possible agreement on the issues raised during the "Lumpy Duck" session, with the ratification of the "New START" pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on the most pressing issues of the lame duck session may not lead to better understanding between the two parties when the 112th Congress meets in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is likely, if not inevitable.
"Once the things that need to be done are done, psychology in the short term will return to one of the confrontations", he said.
Wehner also expressed his widely shared skepticism that civility would lead to genuine cooperation.
"I consider most of what happens between now and 2012 as a pre-show or a shadow-boxing against the main event of 2012", he said.
The reasons for this are closely linked to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and the voters present at the tea party who helped create it.
However, Republican leaders are aware of the dangers of going too far, and they know they must try to live up to their promises to cut public spending and repeal the new health care law.
These partisan positions are already clear in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the deficit committee, which include reforming the tax code and raising certain taxes, pushing back the retirement age and cutting spending.
Co-Chairmen Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have chosen one of the most difficult tasks in Washington and have, in their own words, imposed the deficit issue on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member committee to put their plan out as an official recommendation, and they've had a hard time getting that number.
The greatest resistance remains among the elected members of the group, suggesting that there is little motivation or willingness to compromise on tax issues, at least today.
Galston predicts two phases in the fighting between the White House and congressional Republicans.
The first will come next year in the form of partisan clashes, as Republicans challenge Obama on budget, taxes and health care; to be followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would be the cause of the change?
The public opinion.
There is ample evidence that, despite the partisan spirit of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If the confrontation leads to a deadlock, as in 1995, then both parties will be watching the public reaction closely.
The one who is judged to be a loser will have to change course and compromise.
But that would be an optimistic view.
The partisan spirit and the polarization is greater today than it was in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a greater ideological gap between Obama and the Republicans in Congress than there was then between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a more substantial election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civility displayed this week could be appreciated by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on the part of both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
