"Everyone here likes Ta Mok".
"He was a good leader; and he cared about his people", said 42-year-old Sreng Kor Ma.
Known as "the butcher" for his brutality when he was at the helm of the Khmer Rouge, this commander remains popular in this isolated stronghold of former Khmer Rouge in northwestern Cambodia where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure; and where thousands of former soldiers of the organization still live today.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrendered to the government, longstanding loyalty is finally being challenged in Anlong Veng.
In April, a local truth and reconciliation forum allowed victims to face the people who had participated in the regime publicly.
In June, the government distributed a high school textbook that, for the first time, teaches the history of the Khmer Rouge to the children of its former soldiers.
And in July, a Cambodian court, jointly run with the United Nations, handed down its first sentence against a former Khmer Rouge member, sentencing the former head of the notorious Tuol Sleng torture center, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as "Duch", to 35 years in prison.
This situation has caused increased anxiety among the Khmer Rouge veterans of Anlong Veng, complicating reconciliation efforts and their willingness to reintegrate into Cambodian society.
"There is resentment and fear among the former Khmer Rouge but they are powerless to do anything", said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodia Documentation Centre, an independent body that conducts research on the regime.
"For them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious but the regime became a symbol of evil".
"The situation is causing family divisions".
During the Khmer Rouge rule in Cambodia from 1975 to 1979, some 1.7 million people were executed or died of hunger, disease, or overwork.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew Pol Pot's government in 1979, the rest of the regime and its army fled to Cambodia's border with Thailand.
There they launched a rebellion that lasted until the last of the movements surrendered in December 1998.
While Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary were leading the guerrillas from their base in the mountains of western Cambodia and in the jungle, Ta Mok was planning a sequel in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a UN-sponsored peace agreement led to the country's first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began defecting to the government, culminating in the surrender of Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998 and Ta Mok, who had resisted, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the mountains near Dangrek.
He died in a prison in Phnom Penh in 2006 while awaiting trial.
Without their benefactors, most of the Khmer Rouge veterans have been reduced to the misery of rural Cambodia, and many remain nostalgic for the movement.
Although a few elite Khmer Rouge officers retained their positions as local leaders in exchange for laying down their arms, these are unskilled farmers with low rank and record.
"These people have received very little follow-up after the surrender", said Sok Leang of the Center for Justice and Reconciliation, which organises public forums across Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
"They are imbued with the utopian agrarian ideology of the regime".
"They were raised in an environment where doing business is a foreign concept".
Sor Lim, 55, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle around Anlong Veng before settling in 1998 as a poor rice farmer.
