Recently, during a hot evening, Im Chaem was returning from work in the field near his timber-paved house on a dirt road outside Anlong Veng.
As the sun cast long shadows on the dried grass, Im Chaem refused to discuss his past with the Khmer Rouge.
If the court summoned her, she said, she would refuse to go.
"Cambodia is peaceful and stable", she said.
"If there are more lawsuits, there will be war".
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who defected from the Khmer Rouge in 1978, also warned repeatedly that instability would occur if the court prosecuted several suspects; although experts and historians dispute this.
"Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past", he said.
But facing the past is all Cambodia needs to do to move forward, says Youk Chhang of the Documentation Center.
"Reconciliation in Khmer terms is about reconnecting the broken pieces", he says.
"We need to put these pieces together so we can understand".
The centre produced the first government-approved book on the Khmer Rouge, "A History of Democratic Kampuchea, comprising 75 pages".
