On the contrary, it is another constraint on the difficult process of redefining the euro.
And here Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which clashes with the old traditions of most of its partners.
In the face of European resistance, speculation is beginning in Germany on three possible solutions to the crisis.
The first is a strong euro, which would integrate itself, Austria and Holland, among other countries, and the South would leave the monetary area.
The second is the recovery of the Mark, even though now it seems like science fiction, with a very favorable opinion, almost 50% of the population.
The third is a new conception of the euro, in line with the German proposals for greater macroeconomic control, fiscal rigor, fines for countries which violate them, possible suspensions of payments for one of them and the extension to the private sector of the costs of potential adjustments.
The German position is clear and has been for a long time, so now there is no room for excuses.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission were stimulating deficits, the German Government invented a constitutional reform to prevent them from 2016.
This was the first sign of divergence between what Germany thought should be done (tax rigour and fiscal stability plans) and what its European partners, including France, were doing.
The second blow from the Central European country was when Merkel barely extended the decision to save Greece.
From that moment on, it was the subject of fierce criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and public and published opinion were against the rescue of Greece.
Finally, towards the end of October, Merkel again expressed a clear position, calling for the reform of the EU treaties to make it possible to rescue a country and at the same time to oblige private lenders to bear part of the cost.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, because it precipitated the Irish crisis and the rest.
But his proposal, albeit somewhat sweetened, was approved and in the months to come we should see the process of reform of the Union that will make these measures possible from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not think it will cross.
And it tells us all that, even if we now have to take measures with which we may not agree too much, from that date onwards the old functioning of the euro would have ended.
2013 will mark the birth of a new monetary area, in which countries that break the rules will be severely punished, they may be forced to declare a default and, in that case, the private sector will also bear part of the costs.
Germany is telling us that we must follow a hard path of growth with high saving and investment rates, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness and positive external balances.
