But the red line that Germany has drawn is there, and they don't seem to be moving it.
And one of the possibilities we are considering is to abandon a monetary area which is too full of unimportant countries.
And in that case, Germany can always tell us that they warned us.
Sport and law-breaking
Tricks similar to Alonso and Ramos's against Ajax show ingenuity but not the will to escape a penalty.
The expulsion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) during the November 23 Champions League match against Ajax has caused much speculation about the anti-sports nature of such behaviour and whether the two players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, a few minutes before the end of the match (which their team was already clearly winning), both players deliberately wasted time when they made mistakes in determining the referee to show them the second yellow card.
Thus, and since Real Madrid will eventually be the leader of its group, both players will complete the regulatory sanction during the next game of the block match against Auxerre and can go without cards to the next stage.
Eventually, the UEFA disciplinary committee sanctioned the team's coach, José Mourinho, with two games and various economic sums to the players involved.
Provoking a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, if not rather common in the football world.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, the unwritten but followed rules of the sport.
Part of the debate in the case is due to the fact that this was a team of the Real Madrid entity (which in its anthem displays nobility and honor and has in the past fined its players for similar acts) and the orchestrated dramatization, it seems, by Mourinho, who adds one more episode to his long history of histrionic and provocative technician.
In any event, the debate is on whether this type of behaviour, which is not expressly prohibited by the regulation, is contrary to the principles of sport, that is, whether such actions are in breach of the law, since they are indeed actions which respect the sporting regulations, but which seem to elude their meaning.
The question is to examine the type of damage they do to the sporting spirit.
One of the assets that comprises the sporting spirit is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that has not been endangered by these actions, that is to say there has been no violent play.
Another of these goods referred to with the correct play is to prevent the offending team from taking unfair advantage of the opposing team, which is also not the case.
However, the paradoxical fact of the action of the Real Madrid players is that they do not accommodate themselves to what is normally characterized as cheating or fraud of the law, because their violation of the rules was not carried out in secret to try to avoid the sanction, but their action precisely tried to be as obvious as possible to receive the penalty of the referee.
They waited and they willingly accepted the punishment.
Another question is the type of advantage that offenders derive from the intentional wrongs examined.
It seems necessary to note here that one does not put one's opponent at a disadvantage and one does not gain an advantage in the same match either, because obviously the result of the action presupposes the fact of leaving one's own team with fewer players.
And it's not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club couldn't count on those players.
The advantage is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without any cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indecision, because the team could be eliminated suddenly and apart from that, with this action the players complete a penalty match and move on to the second round of cards, in which the suspension due to the accumulation of cards occurs with one less than in the first round.
So, going up the ladder, it's not so clear that it's an advantage.
In the end, these actions are not contrary to the spirit of sport, which nevertheless includes making strategic decisions that promote the maximum profit that the rules allow.
In our case, the players did not act to avoid the application of the penalty (this would be a clear case of fraud against the law), but rather chose the moment in which they submitted to it.
They made a strategic decision without dodging the penalty or running away from that one.
Although the line between genius and law-breaking is blurred, I think we have a clear case of genius here.
The controversy, I think, arises from two factors: because there were two self-expulsions and because of the way the director was sent to provoke them.
The damage to sporting principles caused by these actions is not so much ethical as aesthetic.
