Pakistan's nuclear program is a major concern in the United States
Islamabad is producing nuclear weapons "at a faster rate than any other country".
WikiLeaks leaks confirm the connection between the Taliban and Pakistan.
The contents of the correspondence between the US Embassy in Pakistan and the US State Department leaked by the Wikileaks portal confirms the enormous concerns that are being raised in Washington about Pakistan's nuclear program.
Apart from the enlightening and tasty details they offer about the content of the conversations and thoughts of the North American diplomatic representatives accredited to Islamabad, the documents reveal the fact that cooperation between the two countries in the field of nuclear security, instead of increasing, is "decreasing" and that the unstable Asian country is producing nuclear weapons "at a faster rate than any other country in the world".
The peculiarity of Pakistan's nuclear program - the fact that the weapons are not assembled, but are stored in components to make it difficult to destroy them in the event of an attack - is one of the main reasons for concern in Washington.
Thus, in a report before the visit of former National Security Adviser James Jones, Ambassador Anne W. Patterson in Pakistan listed: "The proximity of some nuclear facilities to the territory under Taliban attack, the scattering of nuclear materials with low noise, and the vulnerability of nuclear material transport".
The large number of people involved in nuclear arsenals and missile programs is seen, not only by the United States but also by Russia, as proliferating and a reason to maintain vigilance.
"Pakistan has had to hire personnel with strict religious beliefs to protect nuclear facilities; given the declining educational and cultural levels, extremist organizations have more opportunities to recruit people who work in nuclear or missile programs", said Russian Foreign Ministry expert Yuri Korolev during a meeting with his US counterparts.
The new thing in the leaked documentation from the Julian Assange portal is the increasingly reduced cooperation between the US and Pakistan in the field of nuclear proliferation and Pakistan's high degree of nuclear weapons production.
A May embassy dispatch, which described communication with Pakistan as "frustrating", said: "Transparency is often lacking; offers of help go unanswered or are eliminated".
In another message, Peter Lavoy, a National Intelligence official for South Asia, notes that "despite economic disaster, Pakistan is developing nuclear weapons at a faster rate than any other country in the world".
Ambassador Patterson also asked Washington, during a visit by the Army Chief General Ashfaq Kayani, to make it "very clear" to the official that "the Pakistan Army must end its tacit support for terrorist groups".
