The 20th International Police Force based in Lyon, France, issued the order at the request of Sweden, but did not make it public until yesterday, after receiving permission from the authorities of that country.
Thus, the 188 countries of Interpol were instructed to identify or locate Assange "to obtain his provisional arrest and extradition".
Although Interpol cannot issue an arrest warrant for an individual affected by a red alert, many of the member countries, according to the organization's explanations, consider the red notice call a free-for-all for arrest - which the national police force must carry out - especially if they have a bilateral extradition agreement, as is the case with Sweden and England, where Assange is believed to be.
The movement has outraged Assange's lawyers, who yesterday published a letter denouncing the fact that the 39-year-old WikiLeaks founder has shown himself willing to answer questions from Swedish authorities via video conference.
They also recall that Assange sought and obtained permission to leave Sweden from the prosecutor of his case, who is compared to the famous Lavrentiy Pavlovich Beria, head of Stalin's security.
"This appears to be a hunt, not a legal persecution", the letter said.
While the world is searching for him - and in Australia his mother is defending his innocence - Assange continues to be in an unknown place, but he is not silent.
On Monday, he gave an interview to the editor of Time magazine via Skype from an undisclosed location, a conversation in which he called for the resignation of US Secretary of State Hillary Clinton.
"If it can be shown that she was responsible for giving orders to American graduates to spy on the UN in violation of international treaties that the United States signed, she should resign", he said.
