China maintains greenhouse gas reduction targets
The representative of this country at COP16 assured that his country has made enormous efforts to reduce the carbon footprint and detailed that it maintains its offer to reduce its greenhouse gas emissions by 2020 by between 40 and 45 percent.
China is sticking to its pledge to cut its greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, said Su Wei, China's representative at COP16.
In his first public appearance at the 16th Conference of the Parties to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (COP16), Su Wei assured that his country has made enormous efforts to reduce the carbon footprint and rebuild its industry.
In fact, he explained, over the past four years his country has invested $245 million in efforts to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
Nevertheless, he made it clear that China will not change its objectives, but will continue to work together with the international community in this area.
He mentioned that China's strategy in the field of climate change is divided into four areas: dialogue; capacity building; institution building and support for pilot programmes.
Progress has been made in all these areas, including the adoption last year of a new Energy Act, which recognises the targets set for reducing greenhouse gases, he said.
On the other hand, he pointed out that in China, the federal authorities have worked in a coordinated manner with government and local authorities to achieve the targets of energy saving, energy efficiency and emission reduction.
In addition, he said, there are various multiannual plans under way or completed, both funded by the Chinese government and by the governments of other countries.
For example, he mentioned the Energy Efficiency Programme, which has been implemented over the last five years and has received investment from the United Nations (UN), government and private initiative.
There is also a provincial project on climate change, another one for changing incandescent lamps to energy efficient lamps and another one for mitigation and adaptation, he said.
At the same table, Martin Krol, the government's scientific adviser on climate change, assured that China's efforts have been greater than people think.
For example, he explained, per capita greenhouse gas emissions in China are three tonnes per person, while in the United States it is 100 tonnes; China is responsible for 9% of the historical contribution in pollution.
