She comes out of the infectious disease clinic convinced: "Patience is not my strong suit, it may be my wound".
Finally, after a frustrated approach to the trauma doctor who cut his breath in the middle of the hallway, but who explains that wound is not a scientific term; it is the psychoanalyst who reveals the mystery: "the wound is what is actually opened, the symbolic is the scar".
The protagonist sighed relieved and concluded: "On the wound I could only know that it is the one who is open in reality and that it does not exist", but convinced of the fact that the pleasures and traps of the tongue must be closely linked.
Valenzuela, the writer, played with both.
The Nicaraguan Sergio Ramírez also gave a fascinating account, which he called "Praise to the Invention", in which the finger on the wound is not numbered but at some point is discovered.
With touches of magical realism, he tells of a famous sorceress who touched clouds, made people return who had gone far or repaired the virtues that a lady had lost, a narrative that turns to then talk about America, the great news that from the beginning had its own chroniclers and quoted Bernal Díaz del Castillo who criticizes the excesses of the narrations of the conquering captains.
"Cervantes who invented us all (the writers) mocked the false witnesses who appeared in stories presented as real, but in a way that would never have told the history of America with an imagination that lacked even modesty".
Nevertheless, he stressed, "fools and liars have the best imagination" and here reality converges with the lie, it is no longer known which part of the narrative belongs to one band or another, where fiction literature reaches its peak.
This is what we call the Cervantes tradition.
"It's your heritage that makes you what you are".
In turn, writer Mayra Montyero noted and applauded the variety of interpretations provoked by the FIL's invitation with her roundtable Debt on the Wound.
The Cuban-Puerto Rican woman has put her own on the great wound of social violence that her country is going through - and Latin America shares - resulting in drug trafficking and sale disputes.
"I think that good literature, good poetry, good songs contain a tacit commitment that is not of course premeditated", she said, after citing that the reality of literature is the communication and the dimension of the commitment that is established between the author and the readers, and that it is a "chemical reaction" of the latter.
The evening ended with the speech of the Spanish poet Luis García Montero who also stressed "it must be on the wound of the committed writer".
He considered that in a world that is moving at a rapid pace, also in terms of intellectual habits and the control of consciences that is being used to the advantage of dogmatism, "behind every affirmation there is a little no and behind every denial there is a little yes".
"To be masters of our own feelings and masters of reality, we must nuance: and nuancing often means putting our finger on the wound and disturbing people who feel very comfortable thinking in caricature, in black and white, in established and unvarnished ideas and disturbing also the powers that prefer a black and white world", he said, inviting to recover the meaning of writing.
