The European Union changes the rules for obtaining visas
People should go to the Visa Applicant Service Centres before their interview in the Consular Section; the waiting time will be reduced.
As of 10 January 2011, the visa processing procedure at the US Embassy and Consulates will change.
Under the new procedure, most applicants will have to report to the Visa Applicant Service Centres (ASC) before their interview in the Consular Section.
The ASC staff will take the applicant's biometric information, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section before the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for applicants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, no longer needing to make a payment for an appointment, another payment for processing the visa and another for the postal service to deliver the document.
The applicant will make a one-off payment covering all three services.
The current rate will remain the same: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for an on-demand visa (including temporary worker visas) and $390 for a business and investment visa.
Persons wishing to renew their visas will not have to appear for an interview with the Consular Representative, they will only appear at the nearest ASC where they will present their documents and their fingerprints will be taken.
Because the biometric information will be taken from the ASC, applicants who wish to have a second interview at the Consular Section will spend less time than before.
Similarly, visa applicants at the Consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of $26 USD.
For more information on the new visa application procedure, please visit the following page: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
