450 million in contracts without invitation to tender
Hydro-Québec has voluntarily awarded $450 million in contracts to engineering firms for the Eastmain-1-A-Sarcelle-Rupert hydroelectric project.
At the heart of this avalanche of over 100 contracts is a consortium of firms BPR, Dessau, Groupe SM and Axor, which has been awarded the largest, the project management contract, for a sum of 295 million dollars without a call for tenders.
This consortium, called Énergie gérance, was formed in 2004 at the same time as Hydro-Québec decided to entrust the private sector with the responsibility of managing this important $5 billion hydroelectric project.
In early 2005, the energy management consortium won the lucrative contract without a public tender.
The use of consortia of undertakings poses a serious ethical problem for the Parti Québécois, which risks eliminating competition and causing prices to rise.
"This is the new way to collude and kill the competition".
"That is to say, people are now doing it openly instead of doing it in secret", said MEP Sylvain Simard at a press conference yesterday.
Mr Simard raised the matter in the National Assembly earlier this morning because he said he could hardly see how the public interest could be served in this way.
Natural Resources Minister Nathalie Normandeau responded this afternoon, strongly denying that there was collusion for this contract.
"I'm starting to get my journey", she said, claiming that the PQ had been "dishonest" and "lacking in rigor".
She said that "it would be the least of things" for the PQ to apologize.
The consortium formula is a common practice throughout the world.
This is usually a time-limited alliance that allows two or more companies to pool their respective expertise in order to respond to a call for tender for a complex project.
The Eastmain project is highly complex given the scale of the work.
The construction is underway and is scheduled to run until 2012.
However, the contract was awarded without the competition; there was negotiation.
The consortium formula is no longer an exception in Quebec, even for relatively simple projects.
As Le Devoir revealed last week, the consortium formula in the consulting engineering sector is under investigation by the government.
A quick look at the Quebec business register reveals more than 200 consortia, some of which appear to be permanent.
Dessau is working in partnership with most of its main competitors, including CIMA+, Génivar, SNC-Lavalin and other Roche and Tecsult.
Each combination, and there are dozens of them, leads to one and the same moral person, Dessau.
As regards the Energy Management Consortium, Minister Normandeau stressed that "the James Bay area responds to particular labour dynamics and Hydro-Québec has responded to this in a particular way since the 1970s".
