A global plan to renovate lighting
The UN proposed yesterday in Cancun a plan to renovate domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries with a view to achieving a reduction in greenhouse gases (GHGs) that is almost one third of the additional reduction needed to stabilize the planet's climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan follows on from the major concrete projects which the UN hopes will be adopted in Cancun to compensate for the absence of binding reduction commitments by the industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if incandescent light bulbs, which still control 50 to 70% of the market, were replaced by fluorescent light bulbs or, better, by light-emitting diodes (LEDs), most of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of GHG emitted on the planet to light humans would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
That's the equivalent of 70 percent of the emissions from the global car fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitter countries such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans that should bring global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But we will have to subtract another 5 Gt from this balance to stabilize the rise in climate by 2 degrees Celsius by 2020 in order to prevent it from becoming out of control.
In incandescent light bulbs, 95 percent of the energy is dissipated as heat and the remaining 5 percent is produced as light.
With fluorescent light bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, this energy requirement is reduced by a further twofold.
The average life of a fluorescent light bulb is 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
New LED bulbs, such as those being launched by manufacturer Philips this week - the company has also participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, which gives an idea of the possible economy with a replacement plan that would apply to 100 countries.
These brand new bulbs can also work with rheostats and emit very little heat.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Many experts have expressed reservations about fluorescent light bulbs because they contain mercury and must be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries unless manufacturers put in place guidelines.
But, says the report, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the fluorescent light bulb, but rather coal-fired power plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce the electricity wasted in incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury a year.
The report details the gains each country would make from this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save one billion dollars a year in electricity purchases and eight million tons of CO2, the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants that would cost the country 2.5 billion dollars to build.
