Avenging hackers and spies on the run
The WikiLeaks case is a double-edged sword.
On the one hand, it is an apparent scandal, a scandal which appears as scandal only in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between States, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it heralds profound changes at the international level, and foreshadows a future dominated by regression.
But let's go in order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation that every file made up by a secret service (of any nation) is made up exclusively of press clippings.
The "extraordinary" US revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits are just a report of what could have been read in any newspaper (except Berlusconi's own) for months, and Gaddafi's ominously caricatured profile has long been a sketch for cabaret artists.
The rule that secret files should only be composed of new information already known is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not just in this century.
If you go to a bookstore devoted to esoteric literature, you will find that each work repeats (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rose-Croix) exactly what was already written in the earlier works.
Not only is the author of occult texts uninterested in new research - or uncertain where to look for information about the non-existent - but those who engage in occultism believe only what they already know, which confirms what they have already learned.
That's the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
Same goes for the classified files.
The informant is lazy, and the lazy (or limited-minded) head of the secret service (otherwise he could be, I don't know, editor at Liberation), who only holds as true what he recognizes.
The top-secret information on Berlusconi that the American Embassy in Rome was sending to the State Department was the same as the one that Newsweek had published the week before.
Then why have the revelations on these files made such a fuss?
On the one hand, they say what every educated person already knows, namely that embassies, at least since the end of World War II, and since heads of state can telephone each other or take a plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small representation exercises, have become centres of espionage.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it is only through hypocrisy that they pretend to ignore it.
However, to repeat it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy, and serves to cast a bad light on American diplomacy.
Second, the idea that any hacker could capture the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world is a significant blow to the prestige of the State Department.
So the scandal is not so much a crisis for the victims as for the "executioners".
But let's get to the deep nature of what happened.
In the old days, in Orwell's time, you could think of any power as a Big Brother that controlled every move of its subjects.
Orwellian prophecy had been completely fulfilled since, by being able to control every movement through the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway borrowed and so on, the citizen became the total victim of the eye of power.
But when we show, as is happening now, that even the crypts of power secrets cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control ratio ceases to be one-way and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - elected as the citizen's avenger - can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that no longer has the ability to keep its own secrets hold up?
It is true, as Georg Simmel has already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that knowing anything about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is effectively an empty secret, because it is in the public domain; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks did, that Hillary Clinton's secrets were empty secrets means to take away all her power.
WikiLeaks did no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but it did too much to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound inflicted on a very powerful power?
It is clear that in the future, governments will no longer be able to put any confidential information online - it would be like posting it on a street corner poster.
But it is equally obvious that with today's technology, it is futile to hope to maintain confidential communications by telephone.
Nothing easier than finding out if and when a head of state flew around and contacted one of his colleagues.
How can private and private relations be maintained in the future?
I know that my prediction is now science fiction and therefore romantic, but I am forced to imagine government agents traveling in stealth in uncontrolled coaches, carrying only memorized messages or, at best, hiding the rare information written in the heel of a shoe.
The information will be kept in a single copy in locked drawers: basically, the Watergate espionage attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is now advancing in crab fashion, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionised communications, the Internet brought back the wire telegraph.
The video cassettes (analog) had allowed film researchers to explore a film step by step, going back and forth and discovering all the secrets of editing, whereas now the CDs (digital) only allow to jump from chapter to chapter, i.e. by macroportions.
High-speed trains take three hours to get from Rome to Milan, whereas flights, including travel, take three and a half hours.
It is not surprising, then, that politics and communication techniques are now linked to chariots on horseback.
One last thing.
In the past, the press tried to understand what was going on in the secret of the embassies.
Now it's the embassies that ask for confidential information from the press.
Climate: how France is dodging its funding promises
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to review the progress made by developed countries in delivering on their promises of rapid start financing.
And the big French mischief is revealed.
In the Copenhagen Accord, developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has pledged €7.2 billion over three years and France €1.26 billion (or 420 million per year).
At the opening of COP16, the EU played a big game to persuade its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start financing: a report detailing the action of its Member States, a press conference, a major side event, distribution of brochures...
The transparency operation is appreciated and appreciated for its value: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same with the same level of precision.
The EU announced that it had allocated €2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on track to meet its commitment of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But when you look at the details, things are more complicated.
This money must, according to the Copenhagen agreement, be 'new and additional', in order to ensure that an additional effort is made without being at the expense of ODA.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, blocked the procedure.
Today, each person chooses the reference that suits him best.
The European Commission, for example, has taken 2009 as a reference year: international financing is maintained and it is adding 150 million over three years under the Fast Start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar benchmarks in terms of year or level of official development assistance.
On the other hand, France considers that the financing of 'all new projects' in 2010 is 'new and additional'.
In other words, there is no reference to the expenditure of previous years or to the overall level of ODA.
In practice, the total amount of France's support to developing countries may remain stable (or even decrease), and it claims to be respecting its commitment to "new and additional" financing.
Another crucial element is the distribution of donations and loans.
Again, there is no rule and everyone chooses his own way of calculating.
Some, such as France, consider that 1 euro lent is equal to 1 euro given.
Of course, this is hardly justifiable: the effort is not comparable.
While the use of loans can be justified for certain investments which are profitable (often projects related to the mitigation of emissions which rely on more efficient technologies), it is misleading to present a euro which is to be recovered as equivalent to a euro given... At most, only the cost of the loan to the lending country (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate) should be counted as its commitments.
But France has nothing to do with such reasoning: it "meets" its 420 million euro commitment by making 91.5% of loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% of donations (36.1 million euros) - see the EU document to check for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union to use the loan so extensively.
Germany is 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands and Slovakia (among others) are 100% committed.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union puts 1 euro to meet its commitment, France puts only 10 cents and considers the effort to be comparable.
That's a good trick.
In short, France is engaging in a double scam in its fast start financing: on the one hand, on the evolution of the action over time and, on the other, on the reality of the financial effort.
By spending only €36.1 million, it is able to make it appear that it is spending €420 million "new and additional" in line with its promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (for it seems that Bercy has done the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to give if they only lend?) and in the negotiations since the developing countries are not completely fooled...
The early financing chapter is only a small issue, relatively short-term, compared to the whole climate debate.
But it could be just one more grain of sand in the huge machine that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope that doesn't happen.
In any event, it is essential to learn from this first year of early financing.
First, France could announce a change in its accounting method for 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and fairness with other EU countries.
But above all, France could advance discussions on the issues of long-term financing (another crucial chapter currently discussed): the question of 'additionality' or the method of accounting for loans will not be avoided.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
The hope is therefore in the new Minister of the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement on France's fast start and its vision of 'additionality' and the use of loans would raise the level of international confidence needed to move forward in the discussions.
Warning on pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old child ingests 81 different chemicals in a day, according to a study published Wednesday by the association Generations Futures (formerly Movement for the Rights and Respect of Future Generations).
The association, which warns that its results "have no statistical significance in view of the small number of samples analysed, but are illustrative of the problem being treated", bought between July and September the food normally consumed in four meals and one snack a day by a child of about ten years in the supermarkets of the Oise and Paris.
These types of meals, including the official recommendations - five fresh fruits and vegetables, three dairy products, and 1.5 litres of water a day - as well as sweets, were examined by laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals, and other pollutants.
The list is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five are classified as certain carcinogens and 37 are classified as endocrine disruptors (EDs), according to studies by several institutions, including the International Cancer Research Centre.
"Although in almost all cases the legal limits for each chemical taken individually are not exceeded, our survey clearly shows that the reality of consumer exposure to potentially carcinogenic and/or PE contaminants is a matter of concern", notes the association.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible and three proven carcinogenic residues and nearly 20 residues that may disturb the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil and intended as bait for the study, has traces of six chemical substances, including a fungicide which is banned in France.
The same applies to Kenyan green beans, included in the lunch, which the study detected traces of a potent insecticide that is banned in the EU.
In addition, chopped steak, canned tuna, and even bread sticks and chewing gum were riddled with pesticides and other chemicals.
The water from the tap was tested for nitrates and chloroform.
For dinner, the salmon steak was the most "rich" with 34 chemical residues detected and even the examination of the plastic plate used to microwave the meal was not exempt.
The final risk to the consumer of these "contaminant cocktails" "is probably underestimated", according to the study.
The European Ecology-Green Alliance (EE-LV) has proposed, "in view of the urgency of the situation", a moratorium on the use of pesticides in order to stop "the increase in diseases of civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) reported the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruits and vegetables eaten in Europe, 76 of which were in cereals.
